  <section class="cat active" id="cover">
    <div class="cathdr"><h2>Cover to Cover</h2><p>These must be read fully. No summary does them justice. Here is why, and what you are getting into.</p></div>
    <div class="catbar"><div class="bar" data-prog="cover"><div class="fill"></div></div><div class="ct"><b class="ct-done">0</b>/10</div></div>
    <div class="seclbl seclbl-g">General &middot; 5 books</div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="thinking-fast-and-slow" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark Thinking, Fast and Slow as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">Thinking, Fast and Slow</div>
<div class="bk-author">Daniel Kahneman</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Why the full read?</span><p class="sb">Kahneman builds his entire framework incrementally, each chapter is a new experiment that complicates or extends the previous one. The two-system model (System 1: fast, intuitive, automatic; System 2: slow, deliberate, effortful) only becomes genuinely useful when you've absorbed the full body of evidence behind it. Summaries give you the vocabulary but not the intuition. The intuition is what changes how you make decisions.</p><span class="sh">What you'll get</span><p class="sb">You'll finish with a working model of your own cognitive biases: anchoring, availability heuristic, planning fallacy, loss aversion, the focusing illusion, WYSIATI (what you see is all there is), and a permanent habit of asking which system is running right now in high-stakes moments. The chapters on expert intuition, overconfidence, and the experiencing vs. remembering self are particularly dense and rewarding.</p><div class="commit"><span class="commit-l">Commitment</span> About 500 pages. Dense but readable. Take notes. The second half (Prospect Theory, experienced vs. remembered happiness) is where most summaries lose the thread.</div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="meditations" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark Meditations as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">Meditations</div>
<div class="bk-author">Marcus Aurelius</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Why the full read?</span><p class="sb">This wasn't written to be read, it was written as a private journal by a Roman emperor trying to hold himself to his own standards. The experience of reading it is not like reading philosophy; it's like watching someone argue with themselves about how to be better, repeatedly, over years. That quality cannot survive summarization. The repetition is the philosophy. He comes back to the same themes dozens of times because he needed to keep reminding himself.</p><span class="sh">What you'll get</span><p class="sb">A working Stoic operating system: the dichotomy of control (what's up to you vs. not), the impermanence of everything, the obligation to act well regardless of outcome, the discipline of perception, the morning review and evening reflection practice. But more than the concepts, you absorb a tone. A relationship to difficulty, to other people's failures, to your own. That's not transferable in bullet points.</p><div class="commit"><span class="commit-l">Commitment</span> About 170 pages. Gregory Hays (Modern Library) is the best translation, it reads like contemporary prose. Can be read in a weekend or slowly over months. Both work.</div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="the-power-broker" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark The Power Broker as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">The Power Broker</div>
<div class="bk-author">Robert Caro</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Why the full read?</span><p class="sb">Robert Moses never held elected office and yet reshaped New York City more than any elected official in the 20th century. Caro spent 7 years on this book. The argument about how power actually works, how it's accumulated, how it's protected, how good intentions curdle, only lands with full force because you've watched it happen in granular detail across 1,300 pages. An abstraction of the thesis would feel like a conspiracy theory. The evidence makes it undeniable.</p><span class="sh">What you'll get</span><p class="sb">A masterclass in how power operates in practice. How to read political systems. Why reformers consistently fail to undo what entrenched power builds. How infrastructure becomes politics. How one person can bend a bureaucracy to their will for decades. Also: the best biography ever written in American nonfiction.</p><div class="commit"><span class="commit-l">Commitment</span> About 1,300 pages. The longest book on this list. Commit 6 to 8 weeks. It reads faster than it looks.</div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="godel-escher-bach" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark Godel, Escher, Bach as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">Godel, Escher, Bach</div>
<div class="bk-author">Douglas Hofstadter</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Why the full read?</span><p class="sb">This book is an extended argument about the nature of consciousness, self-reference, and formal systems, but it makes that argument through interleaved dialogues, musical analysis, visual art, and mathematical logic. The form is the argument. Hofstadter is demonstrating, not just describing, the phenomenon of strange loops. There is no way to summarize this because the experience of working through the puzzles and dialogues is how the central idea gets planted.</p><span class="sh">What you'll get</span><p class="sb">A permanent restructuring of how you think about thinking. After GEB, you understand Godel's incompleteness theorems not as a math fact but as a statement about the limits of formal systems, including minds. You understand emergence, self-reference, levels of meaning, and why consciousness might arise from sufficiently complex physical processes. These ideas show up everywhere after you've absorbed them.</p><div class="commit"><span class="commit-l">Commitment</span> About 800 pages. The most intellectually demanding book on this list. Not to be rushed. Read it with patience and willingness to sit with confusion.</div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="man-s-search-for-meaning" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark Man's Search for Meaning as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">Man's Search for Meaning</div>
<div class="bk-author">Viktor Frankl</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Why the full read?</span><p class="sb">Frankl developed logotherapy, the theory that the primary human drive is not pleasure or power but the search for meaning, while surviving three Nazi concentration camps, including Auschwitz. The first half is his account of that experience. The second half is the theoretical framework that emerged from it. The theory only carries its weight because you've read the first half. Without the experiential foundation, logotherapy reads like self-help. With it, it reads like something earned at enormous cost.</p><span class="sh">What you'll get</span><p class="sb">A fundamental reframe of suffering: it is not to be avoided at all costs but to be given meaning. The freedom to choose your response to any given situation, the last of human freedoms, which cannot be taken, as a foundation for enduring anything. Frankl's framework for examining whether your life is oriented around meaning vs. pleasure-seeking, and why the latter reliably produces emptiness.</p><div class="commit"><span class="commit-l">Commitment</span> About 165 pages. The shortest book on either list. Can be read in a single sitting. Should probably be read twice.</div></div></details></div><div class="seclbl seclbl-m">Money &middot; 5 books</div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="the-psychology-of-money" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark The Psychology of Money as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">The Psychology of Money</div>
<div class="bk-author">Morgan Housel</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Why the full read?</span><p class="sb">Each of the 20 chapters is a standalone mental model about how people actually behave with money, as distinct from how financial theory says they should. The chapters build cumulatively: each one complicates the last in a way that makes the overall argument richer. The writing is also genuinely exceptional. Housel's ability to use historical narrative to illustrate behavioral principles means the lessons embed differently than a list of concepts would.</p><span class="sh">What you'll get</span><p class="sb">A permanent recalibration of what financial success actually requires: not superior intelligence or access, but specific behaviors sustained over long periods. Compounding is not just a math concept, it's a patience concept. Risk is not just volatility, it's the possibility of being forced to sell at the wrong time. Wealth is not what you earn, it's what you don't spend. These are simple ideas that are genuinely hard to internalize without the 20 chapters of supporting evidence.</p><div class="commit"><span class="commit-l">Commitment</span> About 250 pages. Fast read. The kind of book you finish, then immediately want to re-read.</div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="the-intelligent-investor" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark The Intelligent Investor as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">The Intelligent Investor</div>
<div class="bk-author">Benjamin Graham</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Why the full read?</span><p class="sb">This is the theoretical foundation of value investing, written by the man who taught Warren Buffett. The core concepts (Mr. Market, margin of safety, the distinction between investment and speculation) only make sense when you've done the work to get there. Graham builds his case incrementally, and the later chapters depend on having absorbed the philosophical groundwork in the early ones. Buffett called it the best book about investing ever written. That's not hyperbole.</p><span class="sh">What you'll get</span><p class="sb">Mr. Market: the market is a manic-depressive business partner, not a rational pricing mechanism. Margin of safety: only buy when the price is significantly below intrinsic value, the gap is your protection against being wrong. The investment vs. speculation distinction: an investment operation promises safety of principal and adequate return on analysis; everything else is speculation. These frameworks change how you read every market event for the rest of your life.</p><div class="commit"><span class="commit-l">Commitment</span> About 600 pages (revised edition with Jason Zweig's commentary). The commentary on each chapter is essential, it updates Graham's examples to contemporary markets. Read the chapter, then the commentary.</div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="principles" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark Principles as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">Principles</div>
<div class="bk-author">Ray Dalio</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Why the full read?</span><p class="sb">The book has two distinct halves: Dalio's life story (how he built Bridgewater, the mistakes that shaped his thinking, the near-collapses) and the principles he derived from those experiences. The principles section only carries weight because you've read the life section. Extracted from context, the principles read as corporate aphorisms. In context, they're hard-won lessons from someone who was spectacularly wrong multiple times and rebuilt from it.</p><span class="sh">What you'll get</span><p class="sb">An operational philosophy for decision-making under uncertainty. The 5-step process (know what you want, encounter problems, diagnose to root cause, design solutions, execute). Radical transparency as a tool for eliminating organizational politics. The machine analogy: view yourself and your organization as a machine you design and can improve. The distinction between first-order and second and third-order consequences of decisions.</p><div class="commit"><span class="commit-l">Commitment</span> About 560 pages. The life section reads quickly, it's narrative. The principles section rewards slower reading and re-reading.</div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="den-of-thieves" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark Den of Thieves as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">Den of Thieves</div>
<div class="bk-author">James B. Stewart</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Why the full read?</span><p class="sb">The story of Ivan Boesky, Michael Milken, and the insider trading scandals that consumed Wall Street in the 1980s. The systemic nature of the corruption, how deeply it ran through the most prestigious institutions in American finance, only becomes apparent at full narrative length. A summary gives you the names and the crimes. The book gives you the culture, the psychology, the sequence of rationalizations that let intelligent people build criminal enterprises while telling themselves they were just winning.</p><span class="sh">What you'll get</span><p class="sb">An understanding of how financial crime actually happens, not through cartoonish villainy but through incremental compromise, status competition, and the normalization of increasingly aggressive behavior. The mechanics of junk bonds, hostile takeovers, and the leveraged buyout era of American finance. And a clear-eyed view of how law enforcement finally dismantled it.</p><div class="commit"><span class="commit-l">Commitment</span> About 500 pages. Reads like a thriller. The pacing is excellent.</div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="when-genius-failed" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark When Genius Failed as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">When Genius Failed</div>
<div class="bk-author">Roger Lowenstein</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Why the full read?</span><p class="sb">The collapse of Long-Term Capital Management in 1998 is the definitive case study in how extreme intelligence, model-based confidence, and leverage combine to produce catastrophic failure. Lowenstein builds the story in real time: the founding, the extraordinary early returns, the growing leverage, the slow-motion collapse that nearly took the global financial system with it. The lesson about risk needs to be experienced narratively to be truly internalized.</p><span class="sh">What you'll get</span><p class="sb">A permanent lesson in the limits of quantitative confidence. The specific failure mode: LTCM's models assumed historical correlations between asset classes would hold. In a crisis, all correlations go to 1, everything falls together. Their models said this was statistically impossible. Reality disagreed. This failure pattern repeats in every subsequent financial crisis. Knowing it in your bones protects you.</p><div class="commit"><span class="commit-l">Commitment</span> About 260 pages. Dense with finance but Lowenstein writes it accessibly. No derivatives background required.</div></div></details></div>
  </section>

  <section class="cat" id="cliff">
    <div class="cathdr"><h2>Cliff Notes</h2><p>In-depth summaries. All the key frameworks, arguments, and concepts.</p></div>
    <div class="catbar"><div class="bar" data-prog="cliff"><div class="fill"></div></div><div class="ct"><b class="ct-done">0</b>/10</div></div>
    <div class="seclbl seclbl-g">General &middot; 5 books</div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="sapiens" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark Sapiens as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">Sapiens</div>
<div class="bk-author">Yuval Noah Harari</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Core Thesis</span><p class="sb">Homo sapiens conquered the world through one unique ability: believing in shared fictions, myths, religions, nations, money, corporations. Three revolutions shaped all of history: Cognitive (about 70,000 years ago), Agricultural (about 12,000 years ago), Scientific (about 500 years ago).</p><span class="sh">The Cognitive Revolution</span><p class="sb">Humans developed the ability to communicate about things that don't exist: gods, nations, human rights, legal fictions. This enabled large-scale cooperation between strangers, something no other animal can do. A chimpanzee troop caps at about 150. A nation-state requires millions to simultaneously believe in the same fiction.</p><span class="sh">The Agricultural Revolution: History's Biggest Fraud</span><p class="sb">Farming didn't improve individual human lives, it made them harder, more monotonous, more disease-prone. Hunter-gatherers worked fewer hours, ate more varied diets, suffered less chronic illness. But agriculture enabled population surpluses, which enabled civilization. Wheat didn't become humanity's most cultivated plant because it was good for us, it exploited us as much as we cultivated it.</p><span class="sh">Imagined Orders</span><p class="sb">Money, nations, laws, human rights, corporations, none exist in nature. They're collective fictions that only work because everyone believes in them simultaneously. The dollar has value because we all agree it does. Shared fictions allow millions of strangers to cooperate at scales impossible for any other species.</p><span class="sh">Inter-Subjective Reality</span><p class="sb">Harari distinguishes objective reality (physics, gravity), subjective reality (personal feelings), and inter-subjective reality (things that exist only in shared human belief: money, laws, corporations). These are incredibly powerful social technologies that reshape the physical world.</p><span class="sh">The Scientific Revolution</span><p class="sb">Humanity admitted it didn't know everything and started testing hypotheses against observation. Combined with imperial expansion and capitalist financing, this drove European global dominance from 1500 onward. The key innovation wasn't any specific discovery, it was the institutional acceptance of ignorance as a starting point.</p><span class="sh">Capitalism as a Belief System</span><p class="sb">Credit is the idea that tomorrow's resources can fund today's growth. This only works if people believe in an expanding future. Capitalism is the first system built on the theology of perpetual growth. It has worked, but relies entirely on sustained collective belief in the fiction of future value.</p><span class="sh">The Happiness Problem</span><p class="sb">Despite unprecedented material progress, it's unclear humans are happier than their ancestors. Biology determines a happiness range; circumstances move you within it but don't change the range itself. Buddhists arrived at this insight millennia ago: happiness comes from internal states, not external acquisitions.</p><span class="sh">What to Skip</span><p class="sb">The final third, speculation about genetic engineering, AI, and the future of Homo sapiens. Interesting in 2011. Has not aged well. Far less grounded than the historical analysis that precedes it.</p></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="the-lean-startup" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark The Lean Startup as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">The Lean Startup</div>
<div class="bk-author">Eric Ries</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Core Thesis</span><p class="sb">Startups operate under extreme uncertainty. Traditional management (plans, forecasts, milestone execution) fails here because you don't yet know what customers want. Treat the startup as an experiment. Learn as fast as possible. Validate or abandon hypotheses before burning through runway.</p><span class="sh">Build-Measure-Learn Loop</span><p class="sb">Build the smallest possible thing, measure how real customers respond, learn what that tells you about your hypothesis, feed it back into the next build. The goal is minimizing cycle time. Most startups fail by building too much before learning.</p><span class="sh">Minimum Viable Product (MVP)</span><p class="sb">The smallest version of something that tests a specific hypothesis. Not about building something bad, about learning with minimum waste. Dropbox's MVP was a video showing how the product would work. No product existed. It generated 75,000 signups overnight, validating demand before a line of code was written.</p><span class="sh">Validated Learning</span><p class="sb">The only real measure of startup progress. Not features shipped. Not revenue (early stage). Not lines of code. The question is: what have you learned about what customers actually want? Every action should be traceable to a specific learning goal.</p><span class="sh">Innovation Accounting</span><p class="sb">Three milestones: (1) Establish baseline, what does the business actually look like right now with real data? (2) Tune the engine, can you improve metrics through optimization? (3) Pivot or persevere, is the fundamental hypothesis correct, or does the strategy need to change?</p><span class="sh">The Pivot</span><p class="sb">A structured strategy change based on validated learning, not a random thrash. Types: zoom-in pivot (a feature becomes the product), zoom-out pivot, customer segment pivot, platform pivot, engine of growth pivot, channel pivot. Instagram pivoted from a check-in app. YouTube from a video dating site. The pivot is a tool, not a failure.</p><span class="sh">Engines of Growth</span><p class="sb">Three sustainable growth models: Sticky (retention exceeds churn), Viral (each user brings more than one new user; if viral coefficient exceeds 1, growth is self-sustaining), Paid (customer lifetime value exceeds acquisition cost). Know which engine your business runs on and measure it obsessively.</p><span class="sh">Five Whys</span><p class="sb">When something goes wrong, ask why five times to reach root cause. The first answer reveals a symptom. The fifth reveals a process or cultural failure. Fix the root cause. Toyota built an entire manufacturing culture on this discipline.</p><span class="sh">What to Skip</span><p class="sb">The case studies. They illustrate the framework without extending it. Once you've internalized Build-Measure-Learn, MVP, and the pivot types, you have the book.</p></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="good-to-great" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark Good to Great as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">Good to Great</div>
<div class="bk-author">Jim Collins</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Core Thesis</span><p class="sb">Collins studied 11 companies that sustained performance at 3x the market for 15+ years, compared against matched companies that didn't make the leap. The patterns were consistent, counterintuitive, and repeatable.</p><span class="sh">Level 5 Leadership</span><p class="sb">The single most important finding. Great company leaders are paradoxically humble and ferociously determined. Not charismatic visionaries, quiet, self-effacing, and utterly resolved. They credit luck and others in success; take full personal responsibility in failure. Level 5 leaders build institutions that outlast them.</p><span class="sh">First Who, Then What</span><p class="sb">Get the right people on the bus before deciding where to drive it. Great leaders didn't start with a vision and find people to execute it, they found great people first, then figured out direction together. Be rigorous (not ruthless) about talent decisions. Don't delay hard calls out of misplaced kindness.</p><span class="sh">The Stockdale Paradox</span><p class="sb">Maintain unwavering faith that you will prevail in the end, while simultaneously confronting the brutal facts of your current reality. The optimists died first. They said we'll be home by Christmas, then Easter, then Thanksgiving. The disappointment killed them. Stockdale never doubted he'd survive, and never pretended it would be easy or quick.</p><span class="sh">The Hedgehog Concept</span><p class="sb">The intersection of three circles: what you're deeply passionate about, what you can be the best in the world at, and what drives your economic engine. Great companies operate only at that intersection. Foxes know many things; hedgehogs know one big thing.</p><span class="sh">Culture of Discipline</span><p class="sb">With disciplined people, you don't need hierarchy. With disciplined thought, you don't need bureaucracy. With disciplined action, you don't need excessive controls. Most companies add process as they grow. Great companies hire more disciplined people and hold them to higher standards.</p><span class="sh">The Flywheel</span><p class="sb">Transformation doesn't come through a single defining push or a dramatic launch event. It comes from consistent pressure in one direction over time, building momentum like a massive flywheel. From the outside, the transformation looks sudden. From the inside, it felt like grinding for years with no single breakthrough moment.</p><span class="sh">What to Skip</span><p class="sb">The extended case studies in each chapter. They illustrate but don't extend the frameworks. The concepts above are the entire product.</p></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="influence" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark Influence as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">Influence</div>
<div class="bk-author">Robert Cialdini</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Core Thesis</span><p class="sb">Human decision-making runs on automatic shortcuts. Skilled persuaders (salespeople, marketers, fundraisers, cult recruiters) exploit these systematically. Understanding all six principles lets you use them ethically and defend against them when they're used on you.</p><span class="sh">Reciprocity</span><p class="sb">We feel deeply obligated to return favors, gifts, and concessions, disproportionately to their cost. Give first and people feel compelled to reciprocate. Charities that include a small free gift with donation requests see dramatically higher response rates. The obligation is automatic and resistant to logical analysis.</p><span class="sh">Commitment and Consistency</span><p class="sb">Once we commit to something, especially publicly or in writing, we work hard to stay consistent with that position. Small initial yeses generate larger subsequent yeses. Car dealers use this masterfully: get you to configure and emotionally attach to the vehicle before revealing the real price.</p><span class="sh">Social Proof</span><p class="sb">We look at what others do to determine correct behavior, especially in uncertain situations. Canned laughter works. 9 out of 10 dentists works. The effect is strongest when the others are similar to us.</p><span class="sh">Authority</span><p class="sb">We defer to experts and authority figures, often without questioning actual credentials. White coats, titles, confident tone, all trigger automatic compliance. The Milgram experiments demonstrated the extreme version: ordinary people administered what they believed were lethal electric shocks to strangers because a man in a lab coat instructed them to continue.</p><span class="sh">Liking</span><p class="sb">We comply more readily with people we like. Liking is triggered by physical attractiveness, similarity, familiarity, compliments, and association with good things. Tupperware parties weaponize this, you're buying from a friend, in a friend's home. The product is identical; the social context transforms the transaction entirely.</p><span class="sh">Scarcity</span><p class="sb">Limited time offer, only 3 left in stock, exclusive access, all trigger loss aversion, which is more powerful than equivalent gain. Scarcity is particularly effective when combined with competition.</p><span class="sh">Unity (Later Editions)</span><p class="sb">Shared identity. We comply significantly more with people we perceive as us, same family, same community, same tribe. This goes deeper than liking. It's identity-level compliance.</p><span class="sh">The Defense</span><p class="sb">For each principle: recognition is the defense. When you feel an inexplicable sense of obligation, urgency, social pressure, or authority, pause. Ask which trigger is being activated. Conscious awareness neutralizes automatic compliance.</p></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="the-48-laws-of-power" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark The 48 Laws of Power as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">The 48 Laws of Power</div>
<div class="bk-author">Robert Greene</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Core Thesis</span><p class="sb">Power operates by consistent, observable laws regardless of era, culture, or morality. Most people violate these laws through naivety or moral idealism, and lose power as a result. Understanding the laws is protection as much as it is a weapon.</p><span class="sh">Law 1: Never outshine the master</span><p class="sb">Those above you want to feel superior. Make them appear brilliant. Threatening their sense of position breeds resentment that eventually destroys you.</p><span class="sh">Law 3: Conceal your intentions</span><p class="sb">Keep people off-balance. Never reveal your real purpose. Smoke screens and misdirection are standard tools of power.</p><span class="sh">Law 4: Always say less than necessary</span><p class="sb">Silence creates power. The more you say, the more ordinary you appear. Powerful people speak briefly and make others fill the void.</p><span class="sh">Law 6: Court attention at all costs</span><p class="sb">Everything depends on reputation and presence. Obscurity is worse than notoriety. Be conspicuous. Be discussed.</p><span class="sh">Law 9: Win through actions, never argument</span><p class="sb">Demonstrate; don't debate. Winning an argument creates a resentful loser. Demonstration creates believers and leaves no room for counter-argument.</p><span class="sh">Law 15: Crush your enemy totally</span><p class="sb">Half-measures allow recovery and revenge. If you move against someone, move completely.</p><span class="sh">Law 16: Use absence to increase respect</span><p class="sb">Too much availability cheapens you. Create demand through strategic scarcity.</p><span class="sh">Law 28: Enter action with boldness</span><p class="sb">Timid half-measures generate doubt and invite aggression. Boldness generates momentum and hides uncertainty.</p><span class="sh">Law 33: Find each person's thumbscrew</span><p class="sb">Everyone has a controlling weakness, a secret insecurity, an obsession, a need for validation. Find it and you hold leverage.</p><span class="sh">Law 38: Think as you like, behave like others</span><p class="sb">Nonconformity in thought is power. Displaying it publicly invites attack from the conformist majority.</p><span class="sh">Law 48: Assume formlessness</span><p class="sb">Fixed positions make you a target. Adaptability is the highest form of power. Water wins because it has no fixed shape.</p><span class="sh">The Meta-Lesson</span><p class="sb">Power is amoral. These laws are patterns in human behavior observed across history, not recommendations for how to treat people. Reading them changes how you see every interaction.</p></div></details></div><div class="seclbl seclbl-m">Money &middot; 5 books</div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="rich-dad-poor-dad" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark Rich Dad Poor Dad as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">Rich Dad Poor Dad</div>
<div class="bk-author">Robert Kiyosaki</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Core Thesis</span><p class="sb">The middle class stays financially stagnant not because of low income, but because they think like employees. The wealthy think differently: they acquire assets, make money work for them, and use financial literacy that schools don't teach.</p><span class="sh">The Two Dads Framework</span><p class="sb">Poor Dad, his real father: highly educated, career-focused, believed job security was the goal. Rich Dad, his friend's father: entrepreneur mindset, believed financial education was the real goal. The difference isn't income level. It's the mental model about how money works and who controls it.</p><span class="sh">Assets vs. Liabilities: The Most Important Concept</span><p class="sb">An asset puts money into your pocket. A liability takes money out. Most people believe their house is an asset. If it costs you money monthly (mortgage, taxes, maintenance) with no offsetting income, it's a liability, regardless of potential future value. The wealthy continuously acquire income-generating assets. The middle class acquire liabilities they mistake for assets.</p><span class="sh">The Rat Race</span><p class="sb">Work, get paid, pay bills, need more money, work more. Lifestyle expenses expand with income, requiring ever more work to fund. The exit is building an asset base that generates passive income exceeding your monthly expenses. At that crossing point, work becomes optional.</p><span class="sh">Pay Yourself First</span><p class="sb">Before any bill, set aside money for your asset column. Not what's left over, first, before expenses. The psychological pressure of remaining bills forces you to find additional income rather than defaulting to I can't afford to save. Most people pay themselves last and wonder why the balance never grows.</p><span class="sh">Work to Learn, Not Just to Earn</span><p class="sb">Early in your career, prioritize acquiring skills over salary: sales, communication, management, accounting, investment basics. These compound for decades. A lower salary building these skills beats a higher salary that doesn't.</p><span class="sh">What to Skip</span><p class="sb">The second half, Kiyosaki's specific investment strategies. They're vague, poorly documented, and in several cases ethically questionable. The asset and liability mindset framework is the product.</p></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="the-millionaire-next-door" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark The Millionaire Next Door as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">The Millionaire Next Door</div>
<div class="bk-author">Thomas Stanley and William Danko</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Core Thesis</span><p class="sb">Real wealth in America is largely invisible. People who look wealthy are mostly financed. People who are genuinely wealthy look ordinary, they live in average neighborhoods, drive used cars, and accumulated wealth precisely because they didn't spend it trying to look wealthy.</p><span class="sh">PAW vs. UAW</span><p class="sb">Prodigious Accumulator of Wealth (PAW) vs. Under Accumulator of Wealth (UAW). The diagnostic formula: expected net worth equals (age times pre-tax annual income) divided by 10. Double it to be a PAW. Half it and you're a UAW.</p><span class="sh">Seven Common Traits of the Genuinely Wealthy</span><p class="sb">They live significantly below their means. They allocate time, energy, and money efficiently in ways that build wealth. Financial independence matters more to them than social status display. Their parents did not provide ongoing financial subsidies. Their adult children are economically self-sufficient. They're skilled at identifying market opportunities in unglamorous industries. They chose occupations with low overhead and high accumulation potential.</p><span class="sh">Big Hat, No Cattle</span><p class="sb">High-income professionals (doctors, lawyers, senior executives) are frequently poor wealth accumulators. They started earning late after long, expensive educations. Their professional image requires high-consumption lifestyles. High income and high net worth are completely different things.</p><span class="sh">The Consumption Trap</span><p class="sb">Income creates lifestyle. Lifestyle creates fixed expenses. Fixed expenses require income to sustain them. The wealthy deliberately decoupled their social identity from their consumption level. Most people can't resist the social pressure to spend at the level their income suggests.</p><span class="sh">Economic Outpatient Care</span><p class="sb">Parents who provide ongoing financial gifts to adult children undermine those children's wealth accumulation. The data is consistent: adult children receiving financial support tend to consume more, save less, accumulate less. The gift feels generous. The long-term effect is corrosive to the recipient's financial development.</p><span class="sh">What First-Generation Wealth Actually Looks Like</span><p class="sb">They budget. They buy used cars. They buy modest homes in unfashionable neighborhoods. They don't upgrade their lifestyle when income rises. The frugality built the wealth, not the reverse.</p></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="a-random-walk-down-wall-street" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark A Random Walk Down Wall Street as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">A Random Walk Down Wall Street</div>
<div class="bk-author">Burton Malkiel</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Core Thesis</span><p class="sb">Stock prices follow a random walk, past price movements don't predict future ones. Markets are efficient. Active fund managers don't beat the index over time, net of fees. For virtually all individual investors, the correct answer is: buy low-cost index funds, diversify properly, hold for decades.</p><span class="sh">Random Walk Theory</span><p class="sb">If all available information is already priced into stocks, future price movements are driven by new, unpredictable information, making them essentially random. Technical analysis attempts to predict future prices from past price patterns. On average, across thousands of studies over 50 years, it doesn't work at statistically significant levels.</p><span class="sh">The Efficient Market Hypothesis</span><p class="sb">Three versions: Weak form (past prices don't predict future prices), Semi-strong form (all public information is already priced in, fundamental analysis also fails to consistently beat the market), Strong form (even insider information is priced in, too strong; insider trading does work, which is why it's illegal). Malkiel endorses the semi-strong form.</p><span class="sh">Why Active Management Fails</span><p class="sb">Actively managed funds underperform their benchmark index on average after fees. In any given year some managers beat the market, but their outperformance doesn't persist. Past outperformance is not predictive. The evidence has accumulated for 50 years.</p><span class="sh">The Index Fund Prescription</span><p class="sb">Buy the whole market via low-cost index funds. Vanguard Total Market: 0.03% annual expense ratio. The average actively managed fund: 1 to 1.5%. A 1% annual fee difference compounded on $500,000 over 30 years at 7% growth means over $400,000 in foregone returns.</p><span class="sh">Bubbles Are Real But Unactionable</span><p class="sb">Tulip mania, South Sea Company, 1929, dot-com, 2008, Malkiel documents them all. Knowing a bubble exists doesn't tell you when it pops. Being short a bubble that keeps inflating for two more years is financially fatal.</p><span class="sh">Dollar-Cost Averaging</span><p class="sb">Invest a fixed amount at regular intervals regardless of market conditions. Buy fewer shares when prices are high; buy more when prices are low. The main benefit is behavioral: it removes emotion from the investment process.</p></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="flash-boys" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark Flash Boys as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">Flash Boys</div>
<div class="bk-author">Michael Lewis</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Core Thesis</span><p class="sb">The US stock market is legally rigged. High-frequency trading firms have built a system that systematically extracts small amounts of money from ordinary investors on every trade, using speed advantages measured in microseconds. It's not illegal. It's not fair.</p><span class="sh">The Speed Game</span><p class="sb">HFT firms pay for co-location (servers physically adjacent to exchange matching engines) and proprietary network routes. The extreme example: a $300 million fiber cable was laid between Chicago and New York specifically to shave 3 milliseconds off transmission time. Speed is the entire business model.</p><span class="sh">How the Legal Front-Running Works</span><p class="sb">You submit a buy order for 10,000 shares. HFT systems detect it on the first exchange it touches, race ahead to every other exchange before your order arrives, buy the shares at the current price, then sell them back to your order at a fraction of a cent higher. Across trillions in annual volume, it's billions per year taken from investors.</p><span class="sh">Brad Katsuyama and IEX</span><p class="sb">A Royal Bank of Canada trader who noticed his trades moved the market before he could complete them. Founded IEX: an exchange with a built-in 350-microsecond delay. The delay neutralizes the HFT speed advantage entirely. All orders arrive simultaneously.</p><span class="sh">Dark Pools</span><p class="sb">Private exchanges run by major banks, theoretically offering better execution for large orders. In practice, many dark pools sold access to HFT firms, sometimes the same banks that ran the pool. Institutional clients paying for confidential execution were being traded against by the HFT firms the bank was also hosting for revenue.</p><span class="sh">What It Means for You</span><p class="sb">Use limit orders, not market orders (you set the price, not the algorithm). Index fund investing is a partial defense: less frequent trading means less HFT extraction per dollar managed.</p></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="the-big-short" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark The Big Short as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">The Big Short</div>
<div class="bk-author">Michael Lewis</div>

<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">Core Thesis</span><p class="sb">A small number of people saw the 2008 financial crisis coming by doing something radical: they actually read the mortgage bond documents. The catastrophe wasn't caused by unforeseeable complexity. It was caused by an incentive structure where nobody with the power to act had any reason to see the truth.</p><span class="sh">The Mortgage Bond Machine</span><p class="sb">Banks bundled individual mortgages into bonds, sliced them into tranches by supposed risk, and sold them to institutional investors globally. Rating agencies stamped the top tranches AAA. The underlying mortgages were increasingly fraudulent and poorly underwritten. Nobody checked because nobody was paid to check.</p><span class="sh">The Ratings Agency Failure</span><p class="sb">S and P and Moody's were paid by the banks issuing the bonds, not by the investors buying them. They competed for rating business by offering favorable grades. Banks shopped for ratings the way they'd shop for any vendor. The race to the bottom was structural and inevitable.</p><span class="sh">Michael Burry</span><p class="sb">Scion Capital. One glass eye, Asperger's, read every mortgage prospectus in existence. Identified the systemic fraud in subprime lending in 2005, three years before the collapse. His own investors tried to pull funds and threatened to fire him while the trade went against him for two years. When the market collapsed, his fund returned 489%.</p><span class="sh">Steve Eisman</span><p class="sb">FrontPoint Partners. Discovered the fraud by attending mortgage industry conferences and talking to the people originating the loans. Found that NINJA loans (No Income, No Job, No Assets) were being made routinely and packaged as investment-grade bonds.</p><span class="sh">The Central Lesson</span><p class="sb">Complexity is a tool for obscuring stupidity and fraud. When a financial product cannot be explained clearly, that's often by design. The entire 2008 crisis resulted from an incentive structure where originators, packagers, and raters were all paid on volume regardless of quality.</p><span class="sh">The Uncomfortable Truth</span><p class="sb">The shorts weren't particularly brilliant. They simply read the documents that everyone else was paid not to read.</p></div></details></div>
