<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">Who Moved My Cheese</div>
<div class="bk-author">Spencer Johnson</div>
<div class="bk-concept">Change happens. Adapt early or suffer later.</div>
<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">The Concept</span><p class="concept-v">Change happens. Adapt early or suffer later.</p><div class="divider"><p class="sb">Four characters live in a maze searching for cheese (what you want: job, relationship, money, stability). Two mice, Sniff and Scurry, notice when the cheese starts depleting and prepare to move before it's gone. Two littlepeople, Hem and Haw, get comfortable and deny the signs. When the cheese runs out, the mice have already found a new supply. The littlepeople stay at the empty station waiting for the old cheese to return.</p><p class="sb">Change is inevitable. Waiting for things to return to normal after they've fundamentally changed is choosing to suffer. The people who succeed notice early (before desperation), acknowledge honestly (not this is temporary), and move toward the new thing before circumstances force them.</p><p class="sb">Where are you waiting for old cheese? Which job, business model, relationship, or skill set is clearly depleting, and you're staying out of comfort rather than moving? What's the new cheese you can see but are avoiding because moving feels hard? The cheese is not coming back. Move.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="the-one-minute-manager" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark The One Minute Manager as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">The One Minute Manager</div>
<div class="bk-author">Kenneth Blanchard and Spencer Johnson</div>
<div class="bk-concept">Clear expectations plus immediate specific feedback equals performance. Most management problems are one of these two deficits.</div>
<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">The Concept</span><p class="concept-v">Clear expectations plus immediate specific feedback equals performance. Most management problems are one of these two deficits.</p><div class="divider"><p class="sb">One Minute Goals: Set specific, clear goals with each person. Write each on a single page. The employee should be able to read all their goals in under a minute. When everyone knows precisely what they're supposed to do and what done well looks like, ambiguity vanishes. Most performance problems are goal ambiguity in disguise.</p><p class="sb">One Minute Praisings: Catch people doing things right. Immediately, not at the quarterly review. Tell them specifically what they did, why it mattered, and that you believe in their continued performance. Generic praise (great job) does almost nothing. One Minute Reprimands: Address poor performance immediately when you see it. Be specific about the behavior, not the person. Make your concern clear and brief. Tell them you believe they can do better. End it completely.</p><p class="sb">Audit your management approach against these two questions. Do the people you manage know precisely what success looks like in their role? When they do something well or poorly, do they hear about it within hours, or weeks? Fix both and most performance problems resolve before they become serious.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="fish" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark Fish! as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">Fish!</div>
<div class="bk-author">Lundin, Paul and Christensen</div>
<div class="bk-concept">Attitude is a choice. You can do this work, or you can do this work.</div>
<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">The Concept</span><p class="concept-v">Attitude is a choice. You can do this work, or you can do this work.</p><div class="divider"><p class="sb">Based on the Pike Place Fish Market in Seattle. People doing physically demanding, unglamorous work (throwing fish for eight hours) made it theatrical, joyful, and world-famous. Customers drove across the city to watch. Four practices. Choose your attitude: decide who you're going to be before you walk in. Not I'm excited about fish. I'm going to be fully present and engaged regardless of the task or the weather or how I feel.</p><p class="sb">Play: find the game within the work. The fish-throwing started as efficient product transfer. It became entertainment, craft, performance. Make their day: genuinely engage with whoever is in front of you, customers, colleagues, anyone. Full attention. Real interest. Be present: put the phone away. The person or task in front of you is the priority for this moment.</p><p class="sb">You cannot always choose what you do. You can always choose how you do it. The irony that this book became a mandatory corporate training tool is not lost on anyone, being ordered to choose joy is the exact opposite of the concept's spirit.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="the-secret" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark The Secret as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">The Secret</div>
<div class="bk-author">Rhonda Byrne</div>
<div class="bk-concept">Clarity plus consistent focused action plus daily behavior aligned with your goal equals better outcomes. The universe is not involved.</div>
<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">The Concept</span><p class="concept-v">Clarity plus consistent focused action plus daily behavior aligned with your goal equals better outcomes. The universe is not involved.</p><div class="divider"><p class="sb">Strip out the Law of Attraction pseudoscience, the idea that the universe literally reorganizes matter and events in response to your thoughts. What remains is defensible psychology. Reticular Activating System: your brain filters the constant flood of incoming information and surfaces what you're focused on. When you're intensely focused on a specific goal, your RAS tunes to it. You notice relevant opportunities, people, and information that were always present but previously filtered. This is real neuroscience, not mysticism.</p><p class="sb">Identity and behavior: sustained belief that you're the kind of person who achieves something changes the daily micro-decisions you make, which collectively change outcomes. Visualization: used systematically by elite athletes because mental rehearsal activates similar neural pathways to physical rehearsal, reduces execution anxiety, and builds automatic response patterns.</p><p class="sb">Write down exactly what you want, specific, measurable, dated. Read it morning and night. Spend 5 minutes daily visualizing the outcome in detail. Then take one concrete action toward it every single day. The mechanism is behavioral, not cosmic. The compound effect of directed daily action over months and years is the secret.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="strengthsfinder-2-0" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark StrengthsFinder 2.0 as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-g">General</span>
<div class="bk-title">StrengthsFinder 2.0</div>
<div class="bk-author">Tom Rath</div>
<div class="bk-concept">You will never be exceptional at your weaknesses. You can be extraordinary at your strengths. Stop optimizing the wrong variable.</div>
<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">The Concept</span><p class="concept-v">You will never be exceptional at your weaknesses. You can be extraordinary at your strengths. Stop optimizing the wrong variable.</p><div class="divider"><p class="sb">Gallup research identified 34 talent themes, consistent patterns of thinking, feeling, and behaving that show up predictably in individuals (Achiever, Analytical, Connectedness, Strategic, Empathy, Futuristic, Relator, and 27 others). Most organizations and education systems invest primarily in fixing weaknesses. The data says this is the wrong approach: you can get mediocre-to-adequate in a weakness with enormous effort. You can get exceptional at a strength with the same effort. Exceptional is where the value and the satisfaction are.</p><p class="sb">Take the assessment (access code in the book; standalone version available online). Get your top 5 themes. For each: identify where that strength naturally appears in your current work, seek more situations that activate it, find roles or projects architectured around your strengths, identify your bottom 3 to 4 themes and pair with people whose strengths complement those gaps.</p><p class="sb">The failure mode of StrengthsFinder is treating your results as interesting self-knowledge without changing anything structural. The point is redesign: restructure your role, your team composition, and your time allocation so you spend the majority of each day in strength zones. Manage around weaknesses. Don't let fixing them consume your development energy.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="seclbl seclbl-m">Money &middot; 5 books</div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="get-good-with-money" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark Get Good with Money as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">Get Good with Money</div>
<div class="bk-author">Tiffany Aliche</div>
<div class="bk-concept">A sequencing framework for financial overwhelm. Do these things in this order. Don't skip steps.</div>
<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">The Concept</span><p class="concept-v">A sequencing framework for financial overwhelm. Do these things in this order. Don't skip steps.</p><div class="divider"><p class="sb">The PEACE framework. P - Plan: get complete clarity on your actual financial picture. Document all income, all debts with interest rates, all monthly expenses, all account balances. You cannot navigate without knowing where you are. Most people avoid this step because the picture is uncomfortable. Do it anyway.</p><p class="sb">E - Eliminate Debt: use the debt lasso method, consolidate or move high-interest debt to lower rates, then attack smallest balances first to build momentum. High-interest debt is a wealth destruction machine. A - Account(s): set up the right tools. Checking account, high-yield savings account (not your bank's default 0.01% account), investment accounts. C - Credit: build or repair your score. Payment history (35%) and utilization (30%) drive 65% of the score. Pay on time, always. Keep balances below 30% of credit limits.</p><p class="sb">E - Eventually Invest: only after the above. Investing before you've addressed high-interest debt and established emergency savings is building on sand. Identify your current step honestly. Work only that step until it's done. Sequence is the strategy.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="the-total-money-makeover" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark The Total Money Makeover as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">The Total Money Makeover</div>
<div class="bk-author">Dave Ramsey</div>
<div class="bk-concept">7 sequential steps to financial health. The math isn't always optimal. The psychology is.</div>
<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">The Concept</span><p class="concept-v">7 sequential steps to financial health. The math isn't always optimal. The psychology is.</p><div class="divider"><p class="sb">The 7 Baby Steps, this is the entire book. (1) $1,000 starter emergency fund before anything else. Insurance against life while you're getting control. (2) Debt Snowball: list all debts smallest to largest. Pay minimums on all. Throw every extra dollar at the smallest debt. When it's gone, roll that payment onto the next. Repeat until all non-mortgage debt is eliminated. (3) Fully funded emergency fund: 3 to 6 months of expenses.</p><p class="sb">(4) Invest 15% of household income: Roth IRA first, then 401k to employer match, then max the 401k. (5) Kids' college savings: 529 plan if applicable. (6) Pay off the house early: extra principal payments each month. (7) Build wealth and give: invest aggressively in index funds. Give generously.</p><p class="sb">The debt snowball (smallest balance first) isn't mathematically optimal. The avalanche (highest interest rate first) saves more total money. Ramsey knows this. His insight is behavioral, paying off the smallest debt fastest creates a visible win early. Visible wins produce motivation. Motivation produces consistency over the 2 to 4 years this plan requires. For people who've tried the avalanche and quit, the snowball works because humans are emotional, not computational.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="secrets-of-the-millionaire-mind" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark Secrets of the Millionaire Mind as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">Secrets of the Millionaire Mind</div>
<div class="bk-author">T. Harv Eker</div>
<div class="bk-concept">Your childhood financial blueprint runs your money behavior automatically. Most people never examine it.</div>
<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">The Concept</span><p class="concept-v">Your childhood financial blueprint runs your money behavior automatically. Most people never examine it.</p><div class="divider"><p class="sb">The premise: your relationship with money was programmed by what you saw, heard, and experienced before age 10. That programming runs automatically as an adult and determines your financial behavior more than any knowledge or strategy you consciously adopt. Rich and poor people have different money beliefs at the identity level, not just different tactics. Key Wealth Files: Rich people believe I create my life. Poor people believe Life happens to me. Rich people play the money game to win. Poor people play not to lose.</p><p class="sb">Rich people are willing to promote their value. Poor people think self-promotion is bad or embarrassing. Rich people are bigger than their problems. Poor people shrink from problems. Rich people associate with positive, growth-oriented people. Poor people associate with negative, blaming people.</p><p class="sb">For each wealth file, don't just read it, interrogate your actual current belief. Is your mother's anxiety about money running your investment decisions? Identify the specific limiting belief. Find three pieces of concrete evidence it's wrong. Consciously adopt the alternative belief. Then take one behavioral action consistent with the new belief, because identity follows behavior as much as behavior follows identity.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="you-are-a-badass-at-making-money" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark You Are a Badass at Making Money as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">You Are a Badass at Making Money</div>
<div class="bk-author">Jen Sincero</div>
<div class="bk-concept">The main thing blocking you from more money is your own belief that you don't deserve it, can't have it, or that wanting it is wrong.</div>
<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">The Concept</span><p class="concept-v">The main thing blocking you from more money is your own belief that you don't deserve it, can't have it, or that wanting it is wrong.</p><div class="divider"><p class="sb">The entire book makes one argument: most people who aren't earning what they want are blocked not by lack of opportunity or talent, but by subconscious beliefs that money is bad, wanting more is greedy, or they're simply not the kind of person who has it. Evidence this might be you: you don't negotiate your salary. You undercharge for your work. You avoid asking for business. You don't invest because investing is for rich people. You say I could never afford that without actually calculating whether you could. Each of these is an identity statement, not a financial reality.</p><p class="sb">Apply it: name the specific amount of money you want to make in the next 12 months. Write it down as a number with a date. List every story you tell yourself about why that's not possible for you specifically. For each story, find concrete evidence it's false. Find three real people who started in your situation and didn't stay there.</p><p class="sb">Take one financially uncomfortable action every single day: raise your prices, send the pitch, ask for the raise, open the investment account. The discomfort is not the obstacle. It is the work. Use this as a belief intervention, not a financial strategy. The motivation is real. The tactics are thin.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="cardw" data-read-target>
<button class="check" data-id="the-4-hour-workweek" role="checkbox" aria-checked="false" aria-label="Mark The 4-Hour Workweek as read" tabindex="0"></button>
<details class="card">
<summary>
<div class="sum-l">
<span class="tag tag-m">Money</span>
<div class="bk-title">The 4-Hour Workweek</div>
<div class="bk-author">Tim Ferriss</div>
<div class="bk-concept">Time and mobility are more valuable than money. Stop deferring your life to 65. Design the life you want now.</div>
<span class="readbadge">Read</span>
</div>
<span class="chev" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</summary>
<div class="body"><span class="sh">The Concept</span><p class="concept-v">Time and mobility are more valuable than money. Stop deferring your life to 65. Design the life you want now.</p><div class="divider"><p class="sb">The DEAL framework. D - Definition: figure out what you actually want. Not more money, specifically. What would your ideal Tuesday look like? Where would you be? What would you be doing? What does that life actually cost per month? Usually far less than the undefined fantasy of being rich. E - Elimination: 80% of your output comes from 20% of your inputs. Cut everything else. Low-information diet: stop consuming news multiple times daily. Limit email to two defined windows. Eliminate the 20% of clients generating 80% of your headaches for 20% of your revenue.</p><p class="sb">A - Automation: build or buy systems that run without you. Standard operating procedures. Virtual assistants for anything that doesn't require your specific judgment. The goal: your income continues when you're not the one generating it hour by hour. L - Liberation: work from anywhere. Build mini-retirements, extended periods of travel and exploration throughout your career, rather than deferring all living to a distant retirement you may not be healthy enough to enjoy.</p><p class="sb">The nightmare scenario exercise (this is the actual value of the book): write down the absolute worst realistic outcome if you made the change you're afraid to make. Then write the 10 steps you'd take if that worst case happened. You'll find: (a) the worst case is survivable, (b) you'd know exactly what to do, and (c) the cost of permanent inaction, years of a life you didn't design, is almost certainly higher than the cost of trying and failing. The specific tactics are dated (2007 outsourcing examples). The framework and the nightmare exercise are not.</p></div></div></details></div>
